<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFAlex_Varley.2C_Chief_Executive.2C_Media_Access_Australia2008">Alex Varley, Chief Executive, Media Access Australia (June 2008). <a href="http://www.dbcde.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/84710/Media_Access_Australia_-_Response_to_Media_Access_Review_2008.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.dbcde.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/84710/Media_Access_Australia_-_Response_to_Media_Access_Review_2008.pdf" rel="nofollow">"Submission to DBCDE’s investigation into Access to Electronic Media for the Hearing and Vision Impaired"</a>. written at Australia (PDF). Media Access Australia. 16<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.dbcde.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/84710/Media_Access_Australia_-_Response_to_Media_Access_Review_2008.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.dbcde.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/84710/Media_Access_Australia_-_Response_to_Media_Access_Review_2008.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.dbcde.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/84710/Media_Access_Australia_-_Response_to_Media_Access_Review_2008.pdf</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2009-01-29</span>.  "The use of captions and audio description is not limited to deaf and blind people. Captions can be used in situations of “temporary” deafness, such as watching televisions in public areas where the sound has been turned down (commonplace in America and starting to appear more in Australia)."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Submission+to+DBCDE%E2%80%99s+investigation+into+Access+to+Electronic+Media+for+the+Hearing+and+Vision+Impaired&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Alex+Varley%2C+Chief+Executive%2C+Media+Access+Australia&amp;rft.au=Alex+Varley%2C+Chief+Executive%2C+Media+Access+Australia&amp;rft.date=June+2008&amp;rft.pages=16&amp;rf